# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: credential-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:credential-management/api-credential] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:credential-management/api-credential] It’s been available across browsers since September 2019.
[src:credential-management/api-credential] The **`Credential`** interface of the Credential Management API provides information about an entity (usually a user) normally as a prerequisite to a trust decision.
[src:credential-management/api-credential] Returns a string containing the credential's identifier.
[src:credential-management/api-credential] This might be any one of a GUID, username, or email address.
[src:credential-management/api-credential] Returns a string containing the credential's type.
[src:credential-management/api-credential] Valid values are `password`, `federated`, `public-key`, `identity` and `otp`.
[src:credential-management/api-credential] Returns a `Promise` which always resolves to `false`.
[src:credential-management/credential-management-api] The Credential Management API enables a website to create, store, and retrieve credentials.
[src:credential-management/credential-management-api] A credential is an item which enables a system to make an authentication decision: for example, to decide whether to sign a user into an account.
[src:credential-management/credential-management-api] We can think of it as a piece of evidence that a user presents to a website to demonstrate that they really are the person they are claiming to be.
[src:credential-management/credential-management-api] The guide page Credential types gives an overview of the different credential types and how they are used.
[src:credential-management/credential-management-api] Provides information about an entity as a prerequisite to a trust decision.
[src:credential-management/credential-management-api] Exposes methods to request credentials and notify the user agent when interesting events occur such as successful sign in or sign out.
[src:credential-management/credential-management-api] This interface is accessible from `navigator.credentials`.
[src:credential-management/credential-management-api] Provides information about credentials from a federated identity provider, which is an entity that a website trusts to correctly authenticate a user, and which provides an API for that purpose.
[src:credential-management/credential-management-api] OpenID Connect is an example of such a framework.
[src:credential-management/credential-management-api] Provides information about a username/password pair.
[src:credential-management/credential-management-api] Returns the `CredentialsContainer` interface which exposes methods to request credentials and notify the user agent when interesting events occur such as successful sign in or sign out.
[src:credential-management/credentialscontainer] The **`CredentialsContainer`** interface of the Credential Management API exposes methods to request credentials and notify the user agent when events such as successful sign in or sign out happen.
[src:credential-management/credentialscontainer] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with a new `Credential` instance based on the provided options, or `null` if no `Credential` object can be created.
[src:credential-management/credentialscontainer] In exceptional circumstances, the `Promise` may reject.
[src:credential-management/credentialscontainer] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with the `Credential` instance that matches the provided parameters.
[src:credential-management/credentialscontainer] Sets a flag that specifies whether automatic log in is allowed for future visits to the current origin, then returns an empty `Promise`.
[src:credential-management/credentialscontainer] For example, you might call this, after a user signs out of a website to ensure that they aren't automatically signed in on the next site visit.
[src:credential-management/credentialscontainer] Earlier versions of the spec called this method `requireUserMediation()`.
[src:credential-management/credentialscontainer] See Browser compatibility for support details.
[src:credential-management/credentialscontainer] Stores a set of credentials for a user, inside a provided `Credential` instance and returns that instance in a `Promise`.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] A **federated identity** in information technology is the means of linking a person's electronic identity and attributes, stored across multiple distinct identity management systems.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Federated identity is related to single sign-on (SSO), in which a user's single authentication ticket, or token, is trusted across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and is understood on the level of technical interoperability, and it would not be possible without some sort of federation.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] In information technology (IT), federated identity management (FIdM) amounts to having a common set of policies, practices and protocols in place to manage the identity and trust into IT users and devices across organizations.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Single sign-on (SSO) systems allow a single user authentication process across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and technical interoperability.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Centralized identity management solutions were created to help deal with user and data security where the user and the systems they accessed were within the same network – or at least the same "domain of control".
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Increasingly, however, users are accessing external systems which are fundamentally outside their domain of control, and external users are accessing internal systems.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] The increasingly common separation of the user from the systems requiring access is an inevitable by-product of the decentralization brought about by the integration of the Internet into every aspect of both personal and business life.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Evolving identity management challenges, and especially the challenges associated with cross-company, cross-domain access, have given rise to a new approach to identity management, known now as "federated identity management".
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] FIdM, or the "federation" of identity, describes the technologies, standards and use-cases which serve to enable the portability of identity information across otherwise autonomous security domains.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] The ultimate goal of identity federation is to enable users of one domain to securely access data or systems of another domain seamlessly, and without the need for completely redundant user administration.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Identity federation comes in many flavors, including "user-controlled" or "user-centric" scenarios, as well as enterprise-controlled or business-to-business scenarios.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Federation is enabled through the use of open industry standards and/or openly published specifications, such that multiple parties can achieve interoperability for common use-cases.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Typical use-cases involve things such as cross-domain, web-based single sign-on, cross-domain user account provisioning, cross-domain entitlement management and cross-domain user attribute exchange.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Use of identity federation standards can reduce cost by eliminating the need to scale one-off or proprietary solutions.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] It can increase security and lower risk by enabling an organization to identify and authenticate a user once, and then use that identity information across multiple systems, including external partner websites.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] It can improve privacy compliance by allowing the user to control what information is shared, or by limiting the amount of information shared.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] And lastly, it can drastically improve the end-user experience by eliminating the need for new account registration through automatic "federated provisioning" or the need to redundantly login through cross-domain single sign-on.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] The notion of identity federation is extremely broad, and also evolving.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] It could involve user-to-user and user-to-application as well as application-to-application use-case scenarios at both the browser tier and the web services or service-oriented architecture (SOA) tier.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] It can involve high-trust, high-security scenarios as well as low-trust, low-security scenarios.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] The levels of identity assurance that may be required for a given scenario are also being standardized through a common and open Identity Assurance Framework.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] It can involve user-centric use-cases, as well as enterprise-centric use-cases.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] The term "identity federation" is by design a generic term, and is not bound to any one specific protocol, technology, implementation or company.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Identity federations may be bi-lateral relationships or multilateral relationships.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] In the latter case, the multilateral federation frequently occurs in a vertical market, such as in law enforcement (such as the National Identity Exchange Federation - NIEF), and research and education (such as InCommon).
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] If the identity federation is bilateral, the two parties can exchange the necessary metadata (assertion signing keys, etc.) to implement the relationship.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] In a multilateral federation, the metadata exchange among participants is a more complex issue.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] It can be handled in a hub-and-spoke exchange or by the distribution of a metadata aggregate by a federated operator.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] One thing that is consistent, however, is the fact that "federation" describes methods of identity portability which are achieved in an open, often standards-based manner – meaning anyone adhering to the open specification or standard can achieve the full spectrum of use-cases and interoperability.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Identity federation can be accomplished any number of ways, some of which involve the use of formal Internet standards, such as the OASIS Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) specification, and some of which may involve open-source technologies and/or other openly published specifications (e.g.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Information Cards, OpenID, the Higgins trust framework or Novell's Bandit project).
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Technologies used for federated identity include SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language), OAuth, OpenID, Security Tokens (Simple Web Tokens, JSON Web Tokens, and SAML assertions), Web Service Specifications, and Windows Identity Foundation.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] The Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program (FedRAMP) is a government-wide program that provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud products and services.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] The FedRAMP program supports the transition of federal agencies from legacy IT infrastructure to cloud-based computing environments.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Here is a list of services that provide social login features which they encourage other websites to use.
[src:credential-management/federated-identity] Related are federated identity login providers.
[src:credential-management/federatedcredential] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:credential-management/federatedcredential] The **`FederatedCredential`** interface of the Credential Management API provides information about credentials from a federated identity provider.
[src:credential-management/federatedcredential] A federated identity provider is an entity that a website trusts to correctly authenticate a user, and that provides an API for that purpose.
[src:credential-management/federatedcredential] OpenID Connect is an example of a federated identity provider framework.
[src:credential-management/federatedcredential] In browsers that support it, an instance of this interface may be passed in the `credential` member of the `init` object for global `fetch()`.
[src:credential-management/federatedcredential] Creates a new `FederatedCredential` object.
[src:credential-management/federatedcredential] Returns a string containing a credential's federated identity provider.
[src:credential-management/federatedcredential] Returns a string containing a credential's federated identity protocol.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] A **password manager** is a software program that prevents password fatigue by automatically generating, autofilling, and storing passwords.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] They are useful for local applications or web applications such as online shops or social media.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Web browsers tend to have a built-in password manager.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Password managers typically require a user to create and remember a single master password to unlock the database and access the stored passwords.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Password managers can integrate multi-factor authentication and passkey authentication.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] The first password manager software designed to securely store passwords was Password Safe created by Bruce Schneier, which was released as a free utility on September 5, 1997.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Designed for Microsoft Windows 95, Password Safe used Schneier's Blowfish algorithm to encrypt passwords and other sensitive data.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Although Password Safe was released as a free utility, due to export restrictions on cryptography from the United States, only U.S. and Canadian citizens and permanent residents were initially allowed to download it.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Several other browser-based password managers were launched in the late 1990s including RoboForm (1999) developed by Siber Systems and Obongo (1999), a Sequoia Capital backed company, later acquired by America Online in 2001.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] As of October 2024, the built-in Google Password Manager in Google Chrome has become the most used password manager.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] These are built directly into web browsers like Chrome, Safari, Firefox, and Edge.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] They offer convenient access for basic password management on the device where the browser is used.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] These are standalone applications installed on a user's device.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] They offer strong security as passwords are stored locally, but access may be limited to that specific device.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] These store passwords in encrypted form on remote servers, allowing access from supported internet-connected devices.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] They typically offer features like automatic syncing, secure sharing, and strong encryption.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Designed for businesses, these cater to managing access credentials within an organization.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] They integrate with existing directory services and access control systems, often offering advanced features like role-based permissions and privileged access management.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] These physical devices, often USB keys, provide an extra layer of security for password management.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Others also offer offline storage for passwords, such as OnlyKey and Nitrokey.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Some applications store passwords as an unencrypted file, leaving the passwords easily accessible to malware or people attempting to steal personal information.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Some password managers require a user-selected master password to derive the key used to encrypt passwords stored for the application to read.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] The security of this approach depends on the strength of the chosen master password (which may be brute-forced by an attacker), and also that the master password itself is never stored locally where a malicious program or individual could read it.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] A compromised master password may render all of the encrypted passwords vulnerable, meaning that a single point of entry can compromise the confidentiality of sensitive information.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] This is known as a single point of failure.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] While password managers offer robust security for credentials, their effectiveness hinges on the user's device security.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] If a device is compromised by malware like Raccoon, which excels at stealing data, the password manager's protections can be nullified.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Malware like keyloggers can steal the master password used to access the password manager, granting full access to all stored credentials.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Clipboard sniffers can capture sensitive information copied from the manager, and some malware might even steal the encrypted password vault file itself.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] In essence, a compromised device with password-stealing malware can bypass the security measures of the password manager, leaving the stored credentials vulnerable.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] As with password authentication techniques, key logging or acoustic cryptanalysis may be used to guess or copy the "master password".
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Some password managers attempt to use virtual keyboards to reduce this risk - though this is still vulnerable to key loggers that take the keystrokes and send what key was pressed to the person/people trying to access confidential information.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Cloud-based password managers offer a centralized location for storing login credentials.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] However, this approach raises security concerns.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] One potential vulnerability is a data breach at the password manager itself.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] If such an event were to occur, attackers could potentially gain access to a large number of user credentials.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] A 2022 security incident involving LastPass exemplifies this risk.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Some password managers may include a password generator.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Generated passwords may be guessable if the password manager uses a weak method of randomly generating a "seed" for all passwords generated by this program.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] There are documented cases, like the one with Kaspersky Password Manager in 2021, where a flaw in the password generation method resulted in predictable passwords.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] A 2014 paper by researchers at Carnegie Mellon University found that while browsers refuse to autofill passwords if the login page protocol differs from when the password was saved (HTTP vs.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] HTTPS), some password managers insecurely filled passwords for the unencrypted (HTTP) version of saved passwords for encrypted (HTTPS) sites.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Additionally, most managers lacked protection against iframe and redirection-based attacks, potentially exposing additional passwords when password synchronization was used across multiple devices.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] A 2026 paper by researchers at ETH Zurich analyzed four popular commercial password managers and found 27 attacks in 4 attack categories.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Some vulnerabilities were present because vulnerable cryptographic algorithms were still present due to backward compatibility.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Others were possible because items were individually encrypted which allows field swapping, metadata leakage and downgrade attacks.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Some attacks were possible because of unauthenticated public keys allowing a malicious server to replace keys.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] While most vulnerabilities have been fixed, vendors responded that public key authentication is out of scope.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Various high-profile websites and client-security products have attempted to block or discourage the use of password managers.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Techniques have included disabling password autofill, preventing users from pasting into password fields, or setting `autocomplete="off"` on login forms.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] In 2015, British Gas blocked password managers before reversing the change following public criticism.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Other reported examples included T-Mobile, Barclaycard, and Western Union restricting password pasting, often citing concerns such as malware, phishing, or automated attacks.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] The Trusteer client security software from IBM has included explicit options to block password managers.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Such blocking has been criticized by information security professionals as making users less secure, because it can discourage the use of strong, unique, machine-generated passwords.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Research presented at the 2014 USENIX Security Symposium also described websites using form attributes and scripts to interfere with password managers.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] Modern browser behavior and security guidance have moved toward accommodating password managers.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] MDN Web Docs notes that many modern browsers do not support `autocomplete="off"` for login fields and may still offer to save and autofill credentials.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] *NIST Special Publication 800-63B* states that verifiers shall allow password managers and autofill functionality and should permit pasting passwords when autofill APIs are unavailable.
[src:credential-management/password-manager] The OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet similarly recommends that web applications allow users to paste into username, password, and multi-factor authentication fields.
[src:credential-management/passwordcredential] The **`PasswordCredential`** interface of the Credential Management API provides information about a username/password pair.
[src:credential-management/passwordcredential] In supporting browsers an instance of this class may be passed in the `credential` member of the `init` object for global `fetch()`.
[src:credential-management/passwordcredential] Creates a new `PasswordCredential` object.
[src:credential-management/passwordcredential] A string containing a URL pointing to an image for an icon.
[src:credential-management/passwordcredential] This image is intended for display in a credential chooser.
[src:credential-management/passwordcredential] The URL must be accessible without authentication.
[src:credential-management/passwordcredential] A human-readable string that provides public name for display in a credential chooser.
[src:credential-management/passwordcredential] A string containing the password of the credential.
